<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-216-446  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 216 446.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Feb 19 1990 v16 n4 p22(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>This Unisys plant is full of surprises. (Unisys Corp.'s Roseville,MN, factory automates its printed circuit board assemblyoperations) (company profile)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burrows, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The former Sperry Corp printed circuit board assembly operation inRoseville, MN, was charged in 1983 with turning over inventory sixtimes a year rather than just three times in an attempt to reduceoverhead.andP;  To accomplish this the factory managers initiated anautomation program under which insertion machines and robotsinsert components onto boards, bar-code readers are used in placeof paper and vendors supply ready-to-use kits to the factory floorinstead of individual parts whenever possible.andP;  In 1989 inventoryat the plant was turning over 16 times a year; overhead costs havebeen cut 12 percent annually since 1986, interest costs related towork in progress have been cut between 30 and 40 percent sincemid-1987, and warehouse space has been reduced from 75,000 squarefeet to 35,000 square feet.andP;  Other benefits of the Unisys plant'soperation and how the system was implemented are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Unisys Corp. (automation).andO;Ticker:    UIS.andO;Topic:     Inventory ControlFactory ManagementAutomationCircuit PrintingBoards-CardsIntegrated Circuit FabricationApplicationsComputer-aided manufacturing.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographcharttable.andO;Caption:   Unisys' flexible printed circuit assembly system. (chart)Automation pays off for Unisys. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>